# Plan: `command -v` fallback for binary detection

## Context

`isBinaryInPath` in `src/core/detect.ts` calls `which` on POSIX. On minimal systems (Alpine containers, some embedded Linux) `which` may not be installed. When `which` is absent `execFile` throws `ENOENT`, which is currently caught and treated identically to "binary not in PATH" — so an agent whose config dir doesn't exist but whose binary is installed would be silently missed. Since the project already emphasises portability, adding a `command -v` fallback (a POSIX shell built-in, always available wherever `/bin/sh` is) covers this gap cleanly.

Directory detection always runs first and is the primary signal; binary detection is already a secondary fallback, so this change only affects edge cases.

## Approach

Distinguish two failure modes when calling `which`:

| Error | Meaning | Action |
|---|---|---|
| `err.code === 'ENOENT'` | `which` itself not found | try `command -v` via `sh` |
| any other error (exit code 1) | `which` ran, binary absent | return `false` |

`command -v` is invoked as:
```
sh -c 'command -v "$1"' -- <binary>
```
Passing `binary` as positional `$1` avoids any shell-injection risk (even though all callers today are hardcoded registry strings).

## Files to change

- **`src/core/detect.ts`** — only file touched

### Diff sketch

```typescript
// replace isBinaryInPath with:

async function isBinaryInPath(binary: string): Promise<boolean> {
  if (process.platform === "win32") {
    try {
      await execFileAsync("where.exe", [binary], { stdio: "ignore" });
      return true;
    } catch {
      return false;
    }
  }

  try {
    await execFileAsync("which", [binary], { stdio: "ignore" });
    return true;
  } catch (err: unknown) {
    // `which` not installed on this system — fall back to POSIX shell built-in
    if (isENOENT(err)) {
      return isBinaryViaCommandV(binary);
    }
    return false;
  }
}

async function isBinaryViaCommandV(binary: string): Promise<boolean> {
  try {
    // Pass binary as positional arg to avoid any injection concern
    await execFileAsync("sh", ["-c", 'command -v "$1"', "--", binary], {
      stdio: "ignore",
    });
    return true;
  } catch {
    return false;
  }
}

function isENOENT(err: unknown): boolean {
  return (
    typeof err === "object" &&
    err !== null &&
    (err as NodeJS.ErrnoException).code === "ENOENT"
  );
}
```

The `execFileAsync` import and all other existing code remain unchanged.

## Verification

1. Normal path: `node --experimental-strip-types src/index.ts <dir>` — agents with config dirs still detected as before.
2. Minimal-system simulation: temporarily rename `/usr/bin/which` to something else (or test in an Alpine Docker container) — agents whose binary is in PATH but config dir absent should now be detected via the `command -v` path.
3. No new dependencies introduced.

